alternatives.transcript: reported to the ed this morning she's a sixty two year old female with a cheek complaint of shortness of breath fatigue and dull chest pain she presented to her family medicine physician three days ago to be evaluated she says she had a cold two weeks ago consisting of fever cough rhinorrhea dyspnea and fatigue the symptoms went away five days ago but returned and now she feels worse than before she continued to go to the gym while she was sick but stopped when her symptoms came back she noticed that she sleeps in a chair at night because it helps her breathe better she knows she is comfortable at rest but has dys dyspnea on exertion and with some exercise and orthopnea this places her at a new york heart association classification of class two her past medical history includes hypertension when she takes lisinabril ten milligrams daily for she has no known drug allergies her past surgical history includes cardiac catheter one year ago that showed no abnormalities her mother passed away five years ago due to breast cancer and her father is currently living with alzheimer's she eats a healthy and well balanced diet and before the symptoms started she exercised two to three times a week she denies any illicit drug abuse alcohol and any illicit drug use use of tobacco products and consumption of alcohol she drinks one cup of coffee daily and she's a third grade teacher and she's not being updated on her immunizations and having insurance her review of symptoms is positive for fatigue weight gain of eight pounds over the past two weeks chest palpitations dull again chest pain wheezing myalgia and lower extremity edema her physical exams revealed gvd five basilar rails pmi displays laterally one plus pinning edema in her lower extremities and normal radial dorsalis pedis and posterior cranial pulses her lab demonstrated elevated troponin at point one zero and bnpf four thousand her chest x-ray showed pulmonary edema and cardiomegaly her echo demonstrated dilated cardiomyopathy with a left ventricular ejection fraction of less than thirty percent her ekg indicated sinus tachycardia right bundle branch block left axis deviation and preventricular contractions her vitals showed temperature of ninety eight point six elevated heart rate of one ten elevated respiratory rate of twenty elevated blood pressure of one thirty over ninety and her o two was slightly decreased at ninety one percent so based on her history exam findings and the diagnostic workups i believe that miss palmer has a myocarditis dilated cardiomyopathy new york heart association class two which is serious condition i think the best point of action would be to admit her to telemetry to monitor her vitals every two hours she can proceed with activity as tolerated and she would be monitored by nursing for shift io daily weight dvt prophylaxis o two nasal cannula to nineteen o two stats greater than ninety six percent and her saline fluid should be kbo and her diet should be low sodium and food restriction a two day i believe a two day echo should be repeated she should continue her lisinopril ten milligrams daily and begin or she should continue her lisinopril ten milligrams daily and begin furosemide forty milligrams iv over twelve hours and acetaminophen six hundred twenty five milligrams every six hours acmp and serial troponin should be ordered a consult with interventional cardiology infectious disease and radiology should be conducted to place in ai cd and crtd and an endomyocardial biopsy should also be completed a media enhanced mri should be completed and her immuno immunoglobulins and glucocorticoids should be evaluated and that is the end of my case presentation thank you for your time
